[u'Senior VP of Business Operations
Allen Harrison Company
November 2014 to January 2015
• Manage the daily operations of Property Management division, Quality Assurance, and Renovation Department.
• Supervise the Transition Management Team in opening procedures of all new development, acquisitions and dispositions of Company assets.
• Oversee quality control measures in the Construction, Operations, Renovations, and Property Management Departments.
• Responsible for employee relations with the Human Resources Department.
• Partner with the Development Division in new asset design and planning process.
• Supervise the property management regional supervisors.
• Responsible for investor relations regarding ongoing operations and site inspections with investor representatives.', u'Vice President of Quality Assurance
The Hanover Company - Houston, TX
January 1991 to January 2014
• Developed the QA Department after managing the Scheduling, Warranty, and Disposition Departments;
• Managed a multi-family national portfolio of A+ properties throughout the US, at peak levels, approx. 9000 units with a total capitalization cost of 2.8 billion;
• Supervised over 35 direct reports and was responsible for 29 projects under various stages of development; including hi-rise, mid-rise and garden style properties;
• Implemented two tiered department structure for Property Management consisting of a Turnover Specialist Team and a Facilities Management Team which included developing the policies and procedures to execute the new structure;
• Chief Quality Assurance officer of large multi-family real estate development and management company employing, at peak levels, 600 employees;
• Oversee quality control measures in both Construction and Property Management;
• Train and administer company policies and procedures;
• Create and conduct employee training programs, including Fair Housing, Sexual Harassment, Facilities Management, Risk Management, and Fire and Life Safety;
• Partner with and manage in house risk management team in legal matters;
• Oversaw the formation, build-out, and opening of eight satellite offices throughout the nation;
• Responsible for all build-outs at the corporate office:;
• Led facility management and operations-related due diligence in recent disposition of twenty nine company owned assets;
• Provided innovative property management solutions and systems;
• Opened and operated multiple properties as Maintenance Supervisor;']

[u"Consultant/Project Manager
Integrated Pharmacy Solutions - Melrose, MA
September 2017 to November 2017
Assists Pharmacy Benefit Managers (PBM), Qualified Health Plans (QHP), and other clients in the development and deployment of strategies to identify network providers that may be at risk for fraud, waste and abuse, i.e., pharmacy providers (hospital, retail, specialty, home infusion, long term care), and physician's practices. Make recommendations for steps to improve networks, take necessary steps to eliminate providers, and/or suggest further actions to maintain compliance to network requirements.", u'President/Owner/Pharmacist
NortheastRx, Inc. dba/ Cape Cod Home Infusion Services - North Falmouth, MA
May 2006 to February 2015
Acquired, developed, and operated an independent specialty and home infusion pharmacy serving Southeastern Massachusetts. Successfully implemented clinical and quality programs that met the needs of the market, including: specialty pharmacy, oncology, nutritional support, antimicrobial therapies, hospice and palliative, and specialty drugs for patients with chronic conditions. Established differentiation from competitors by verifying, designing, dispensing, and delivering safe and effective pharmaceuticals to patients’ in their homes, both accurately and on-time. (i.e., delivering drugs and related equipment and supplies to patients’/caregivers’ homes within 4 hours of receipt of a valid prescription, 24 hours a day, at a success rate of ninety-nine percent 99% ). Consistently exceeded USP <797>, BOP, DEA, and insurer’s requirements. Implemented clinical and quality programs that improved the delivery of products and services to patients, and resulted in improved collaboration with patients, caregivers, and prescribers. After experiencing a devastating fire in 2011, re-engineered the business.', u'VP of Pharmacy Operations
Accredo Health Group, Inc - Memphis, TN
September 1994 to May 2006
Responsible for the management of a multi-site (18 locations) centralized and decentralized mail-order pharmacy operations for specialty medications with over $1.3B in annual sales, and over 300 branch personnel reporting to VP Pharmacy, over 100,000 patients and 1.3M prescription fills/shipments per year.
Implemented monthly staff meetings for 300 associates to keep them informed which resulted in improved worked performance and morale. Communications included: status of revenue and expense targets, quality benchmark results, operational improvements and successes, updates with new clients, new products, new policies, procedures and processes, acknowledge outstanding associate performance, and obtain significant feedback from associates.

Successfully implemented and re-engineered proprietary operating systems that supported on-site and remote services including: patient intake and assessment; insurance verification, benefit qualifications, and prior authorizations; patient clinical monitoring and management for: pharmacy, nursing, customer service, social services, and registered dietitians; prescription dispensing and distribution; inventory supply-chain management; product vendor interface; interface with shipping logistics and supply chain management carriers; remote access for prescriber, managed care, and pharmaceutical manufacturer; product and service billing, claims adjudication and reconciliation; accounts receivables; and interface with financial services; full battery of customizable reports; and industry compliant security.

Participated in the management and integration of mergers and acquisitions including: the consolidation of pharmacies; the integration and/or downsizing of pharmacy personnel, and standardizing of policy, procedure, and process flows, etc.

Re-engineered the central distribution of specialty drugs including: the redesigned of warehouse facilities (receiving, inventory management, drug storage); security and integrity of inventory, (automated temperature recording, monitoring and reporting of the integrity of $100M of pharmaceuticals); maintaining the integrity and controls of the supply chain, from drug manufacturer to delivery of pharmaceutical and supplies to patient/caregivers’ homes, or prescriber/clinics offices.

Co-Implemented Six-Sigma quality re-engineering, benchmarking, and reporting programs for: patient clinical monitoring, packaging, and distribution of specialty pharmaceuticals. Successfully completed Six-Sigma Black-Belt Training (Mark Wegryn, Trainer).

Worked with national sales management in creating marketing materials and presentations based on industry and client-specific drug utilization and other clinical data.

Participated in development of an infusion network for Carecentrix, a national provider network for home care services for managed care and other health care organizations. The infusion program identifies and recommends targeted drugs that may be appropriate to transition from higher cost settings to home; optimizes provider networks based on specific drug therapies, and collects and monitors provider data to determine how patients are responding to therapy.

Developed a cost savings model that improved branch contribution by over $4M annually;
Implemented staffing and process models that enabled branch staff to improve processes to keep operating expense growth to a minimum;

Developed a standardized cost and pricing model for capitation and fee-for service contracts that enabled growth of new product lines;

Developed and implemented job aides, training programs, and pre-Joint Commission credentialing programs;

Developed payer guidelines which enabled Company and insurers to save over $3M in outlier drug costs.

Implemented programs for specialty pharmaceuticals that are prescribed for persons with complex and/or chronic medical conditions, and rare or orphan disease indications which meet the following criteria:
• Requires additional patient education, adherence (persistency and compliance), and support beyond traditional dispensing activities;
• Requires unique storage or shipment requirements, such as refrigeration;
• Is not stocked at a majority of retail pharmacies;
• Meet additional FDA requirements imposed during the drug approval process;
• Track drug inventory to prevent diversion and counterfeiting;
• Maintain the integrity and quality of drugs as they move through the supply channel;
• Ensure that special dosing and lab monitoring requirements are followed;
• Health care provider access: Specially trained pharmacists, nurses, and clinicians are accessible to patients around the clock to provide guidance and insight on disease states, as well as the use and management of specialty drugs;
• Physician consultations: Consults directly with physicians to address patient side effects, adverse drug reactions, non-compliance, and other patient concerns;
• Care management: Performs disease and drug-specific patient care management services that meet the unique needs of each patient and incorporate multiple safeguards when dispensing and delivering the drug to ensure patient safety;
• Clinical outcome measures: Collects data and tracks outcomes for specific patients;
• Patient adherence programs: Manages patient adherence/compliance, and persistency of drug regimens;
• REMS programs: Manages care for manufacturer Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS) program requirements, including REMS reporting, Phase IV trials, the dispensing of FDA trial drugs under strict protocols, and related clinical and cognitive counseling;
• Operational Services Supply chain management: Adheres to rigorous storage, shipping, and handling standards to meet product label shipping requirements, such as temperature control and the timely delivery of products in optimal and suboptimal conditions;
• Care coordination: Offers coordinating services with other health care providers, including those providing skilled nursing services, custodial care, infusion administration, and direct-to-physician distribution and administration in clinics or prescriber offices ;
• Insurance navigation: Expedites access to therapy by working directly with insurers and navigating their benefits, utilization management, and prior authorization processes;
• Patient assistance: Facilitates eligible patients’ enrollment in patient assistance programs and access to charitable resources;
• Plan optimization: Aligns economic incentives across medical and pharmacy benefits while helping patients navigate the complexity of sometimes-siloed benefit structures;']
